    <item>
      <title>15.01 Older Brother&amp;#8217;s Care</title>
      <link>https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-01-older-brothers-care/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-01-older-brothers-care/</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 25 Aug 2025 14:57:13 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;main class="wp-block-group is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow"&gt; &lt;div class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"&gt;&lt;h1 class="wp-block-post-title"&gt;15.01 Older Brother&amp;#8217;s&amp;nbsp;Care&lt;/h1&gt;   &lt;div style="height:1px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;div class="entry-content wp-block-post-content is-layout-constrained wp-block-post-content-is-layout-constrained"&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;T/N: So the WN has resumed and I&amp;#8217;m already hit with the quandary of picking the best translation for titles. The arc title especially, but I&amp;#8217;ll talk about it at the end of this chapter.&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;The chapter title seems to be going for the two senses of the word: 1) to help things grow or develop; 2) a place that looks after kids i.e. day care/nursery/childcare&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" /&gt;    &lt;p&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-24-houkou/"&gt;Previous Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The sound of soil being tilled filled the air.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao gazed absently at the man working the fields with her chin resting on her hand.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;They were just outside the castle walls of the capital—where the field Maomao and her adoptive father Luomen cultivated was. No, where it used to be.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The guards had turned a blind eye to the field in exchange for them dealing with the kudzu that clung to the walls, however…&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The field hadn’t received proper care for the past couple of years. It had been left to run wild.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Nevertheless, the kudzu on the wall was the only thing completely cleared away.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;When was it again that the kudzu got eradicated?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She remembered bringing Sazen and Kokuyou along to harvest the plant.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Back then, she had known nothing about Kokuyou’s true nature. As she hadn’t known, she naïvely believed that he wasn&amp;#8217;t a bad person.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Right now, the one on the field wasn’t Luomen nor Sazen.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“This place is great!”&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was Rahan’s older brother, wiping the sweat off his brow with a lively expression.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Apparently he had ploughed and ploughed the garden at the weirdo tactician’s residence and when he proceeded to plough even outside the residence, he was told that he wasn&amp;#8217;t allowed to do that.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;That goes without saying.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;And it was for that reason he came to ask Maomao for any suitable land. After reserving the field at the dilapidated shack at the pleasure district to grow medicinal herbs, this was the only place serviceable.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Rahan’s older brother is always in good spirits, huh?” she said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Health is wealth, after all. You gotta eat well, sleep well and move well,” he answered.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What are you growing?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;There didn’t seem to be anything that could be grown considering the season. Looking at Rahan’s older brother would make you feel like it was sweltering, but the air he breathed out was white.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Nah, I wasn’t thinking about growing anything specific. I just thought about preparing for cold season cultivation and soil improvement.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It’s not a countermeasure against locusts either, right?” Even Maomao knew that turning up the soil worked to prevent locust outbreaks. She had done more than enough of it.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Well, for the time being, scatter these for me.” Rahan’s older brother pointed to a large sack. She peered inside to see shells that had been grounded into powder.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You guys help me out, too,” he called out.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;““Okaaaay.””&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Children gathered around Rahan’s older brother.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Sifan, Wufan, Liufan, Junjie, and then Zhizi.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;It became an odd group.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao crossed her arms and looked on in amazement.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Junjie aside, it was odd to see Zhizi blending in with them. She had been such a sickly young lady when she came in, and yet she was currently clad in dirty clothes and straw boots. It might not be snowing, but it was cold outside.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Who would think that the child with flushed cheeks scattering powdered shell was the empress dowager’s niece and the emperor’s cousin?&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The girl was having so much fun that Maomao loathed to stop her. More importantly, it was delightful to see her running around energetically. Her starved beast period had been shocking, but it seems the girl had pretty much settled down nowadays.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Heeey, you’ve scattered too much there. You have to scatter it around evenly. If you don’t do it properly, the crops will grow badly.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Okaaaay.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Upon hearing such an obedient reply, Maomao was reminded of Chou’u, who was in his rebellious age, at the pleasure district.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;If I leave him with Rahan’s older brother, would he become obedient?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Rahan’s older brother was popular, but he wasn’t ambitious. So far as it goes, he had the desire to succeed in life by getting rich like an average person, but his current look suited him too well.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Come to think of it, Rahan had tricked him into going to the western capital.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Although Rahan’s older brother’s name hadn’t been recorded, his achievements might be passed down in the western lands for generations to come.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Just don’t start an uprising.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She could only imagine him leading the peasants with a hoe in hand, were he to start some rebellion.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Heeey, Rahan’s younger sister. If you’re idle, help out,” Rahan’s older brother called out. He could call Maomao ‘Rahan’s younger sister’ every now and then. Normally, she would cut back with a “I’m not his sister,” but she would let it slide at times for Rahan’s older brother.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Rather than me being idle, weren’t you the one to ask me to bring you to a place that could become a field?” she said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“But moving your body once in a while will do you good. Just now the expression you made seemed like you were at your wits’ end.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“…”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Seems like he sensed that she was distressed by something.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;He’s oddly sharp.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;But he didn’t pry.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao was distressed over how she should deal with the existence known as Kokuyou.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The man was harmless to those who were harmless, and harmful to those who were harmful. For a living being, his actions were just.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She wanted to believe it would be fine to have him hang around Verdigris Mansion with how things were. Sazen, whom she had left to manage the apothecary, wasn’t a bad person by nature. The madam may be a miser, but she doesn’t conduct criminal business.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;If it were Maomao in the past, she would simply turn a blind eye. However, having been in contact with people who were close to the law, she ended up getting distressed over whether Kokuyou should be punished for straying from the path so many times.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Rahan’s older brother had discerned what Maomao had been distressed over. “You look like you&amp;#8217;re thinking about something you can do nothing about.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes, I&amp;#8217;m thinking about something I can do nothing about.” Maomao let out a big sigh.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;What would be Maomao’s guiding principles at a time like this?&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I’m just wasting time by thinking about something where thinking won’t give me answers&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Set it aside for now. Do what she could do now.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I’ll forget about it for now and do some work.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That’s the spirit. Rather, it would be great if Rahan could come along too. That guy is top heavy and doesn’t exercise at all.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Rahan would be out of commission the day after.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You’re right.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao took the hoe from Rahan’s older brother and went to till the powdered shell into the ground.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;After working in the fields, Maomao parted ways with Rahan’s older brother’s group midway. She hadn’t intended to work with soil, so she hadn’t brought a change of clothes with her.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;As there was no way she would return to the dorms covered in dirt, she decided to stop by the pleasure district.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Woah, you’re dirty.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Chou’u was at the dilapidated shack Maomao used to live in. It seems the brat, who was in the middle of his rebellious phase, had overtaken Maomao’s height.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I’m just here for a change of clothes,” she said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“…” Chou’u’s mood immediately soured and he left the shack.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What an attitude.” Maomao, paying no mind to it, opened up an old wicker trunk. There were a few sets of tasteless clothes she got from a second hand shop previously. She thought these would be much better than being covered in dirt, and it was that moment someone beat at her shoulders.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It turned out to be Zilin. Chou’u had grown up, but Zilin had grown a lot too. The girl was still treated as a kamuro, but at this rate, in two years even, she would be taking in clients.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What’s the matter?” Maomao asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The girl was the goldfish poop that always stuck behind Chou’u.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Zilin looked like she had a lot to say, but she was mute. She could hear, but she couldn’t speak. Maomao heard the girl had never spoken since she was born. There could be some abnormalities with her throat from birth, or she lost the ability to speak from an illness or an injury before she could learn how to speak.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;As a herbalist, Maomao would like to find out what caused it, but that would be difficult since it wasn’t her field of expertise.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Zilin brought over a box filled with sand.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;Chou’u has been acting strange lately&lt;/em&gt;,” the girl wrote. It seems she had been taught to write to make up for her inability to speak.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Does he act like that to people aside from me?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;I don’t mean that.&lt;/em&gt;” Zilin groaned, at a loss for how to write it. “&lt;em&gt;He’s obsessing over it&lt;/em&gt;.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Over what?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Zilin eagerly took out a book from her bosom pocket. The book was covered in finger marks from being read many times.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;He has been acting strange ever since he read this book&lt;/em&gt;.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;Is that so?”&amp;nbsp; Maomao tapped the girl on the head. “I’m going to borrow this.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;Okay.&lt;/em&gt;”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao took the book.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was titled: ‘The Villainess of the North’.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" /&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;T/N: Zilin = Zuurin, but now more faithful to the Mandarin reading.&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;Going by this chapter, I&amp;#8217;m hazarding that this arc seems to be about Maomao dealing with the fallout from the revelation of Kokuyou&amp;#8217;s true nature, and the ramifications of Chou&amp;#8217;u coming to terms to what happened to the Shi clan&amp;#8230; so I&amp;#8217;ll temporarily dub this arc &amp;#8220;Dealing with the Repercussions&amp;#8221;, or just Repercussions because one word titles are best. I will change it later. &lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;Otherwise other possible translation that are truer to the literal meaning of the word: &amp;#8220;Dealing with the aftermath&amp;#8221; &amp;#8220;Setting things right&amp;#8221; &amp;#8220;Picking up the pieces&amp;#8221; &amp;#8220;Cleaning up the mess&amp;#8221; &amp;#8220;Tying up loose ends&amp;#8221; &amp;#8220;Settling the matter/problem&amp;#8221; &amp;#8220;Straightening things out&amp;#8221; &amp;#8220;Making up for mistakes&amp;#8221;  &lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;Hard to judge if the title is going for the positive or negative sense right now.&lt;/sub&gt; &lt;sub&gt;Knowing Boar, probably both.&lt;/sub&gt; &lt;sub&gt;So far, I&amp;#8217;m leaning towards &amp;#8220;setting thing right.&amp;#8221;&lt;/sub&gt; &lt;sub&gt;Thoughts?&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;Gosh does this sound like the title of a final arc&amp;#8230;. &lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;But why am I thinking so hard about this? In the long run, the best translation doesn&amp;#8217;t matter too much, since the only version that matters in the end is Kevin&amp;#8217;s anyway 🙂&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p class="has-text-align-right"&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-02-the-story-of-the-villainess/"&gt;Next Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div id="jp-post-flair" class="sharedaddy sd-like-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-official sd-sharing"&gt;&lt;h3 class="sd-title"&gt;Share this:&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="sd-content"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li class="share-facebook"&gt;&lt;div class="fb-share-button" data-href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-01-older-brothers-care/" data-layout="button_count"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li class="share-end"&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-130534757-5521-68e0e56ed46bc' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/index.html?ver=20251004#blog_id=130534757&amp;amp;post_id=5521&amp;amp;origin=shikarito.wordpress.com&amp;amp;obj_id=130534757-5521-68e0e56ed46bc' data-name='like-post-frame-130534757-5521-68e0e56ed46bc' data-title='Like or Reblog'&gt;&lt;div class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height: 55px;'&gt;&lt;span class='button'&gt;&lt;span&gt;Like&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class='loading'&gt;Loading&amp;#8230;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span class='sd-text-color'&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a class='sd-link-color' href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-01-older-brothers-care/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/main&gt;</description>
